/*
  # Additional Medical Billing Glossary Terms - Part 2
  
  ## Overview
  Expands the glossary with additional specialized terms covering:
  - Advanced coding concepts
  - Payer-specific terminology  
  - Practice management operations
  - Value-based care and MACRA
  - Credentialing and contracting
  - Patient financial services
  - Healthcare technology
  
  ## Notes
  This migration adds 50+ more terms to create a comprehensive resource
  covering all aspects of medical billing and revenue cycle management.
*/

-- More coding and billing terms
INSERT INTO glossary_terms (term, definition, detailed_explanation, example, why_it_matters, category, related_terms) VALUES
('Place of Service (POS)', 'A two-digit code on claims indicating where services were rendered.', 'POS codes identify the location where healthcare services are provided and affect reimbursement rates and coverage determinations. Common codes include: 11 (office), 12 (home), 21 (inpatient hospital), 22 (outpatient hospital), 23 (emergency room), 24 (ambulatory surgical center), 31 (skilled nursing facility), and many others. Incorrect POS codes cause claim denials or incorrect payment. Some services are only covered in specific settings - for example, certain preventive services may require POS 11 (office). Payment rates often vary by POS - the same procedure may pay more in an office (POS 11) versus hospital outpatient (POS 22). Medicare and commercial payers have specific POS requirements. The POS must match actual service location to avoid compliance issues.', 'A cardiologist performs an office visit (POS 11) and bills 99214. Later that week, the same physician sees the patient in the hospital (POS 21) and bills 99232 for hospital follow-up. The office visit (POS 11) pays at the non-facility rate ($112), while the hospital visit (POS 21) pays at the facility rate ($75) because hospital overhead is factored into the hospital''s payment.', 'Incorrect POS coding can result in claim denials, incorrect payments, or compliance violations. Using the wrong POS to obtain higher payment is considered fraud. Some payers are very particular about POS requirements, especially for services that are location-specific. Practices with multiple service locations must ensure staff understand proper POS coding for each site. Facility versus non-facility payment rates create significant reimbursement differences based on POS.', 'Medical Coding', ARRAY['CPT Code', 'Non-Facility Rate', 'Facility Rate', 'Claim Denial']),

('Global Period', 'A time frame following surgery during which all related care is included in the surgical payment and cannot be separately billed.', 'Surgical procedures have global periods of 0, 10, or 90 days. During the global period, all related services are included: pre-operative visits (typically 1 day before for major procedures), the surgery itself, and post-operative care (complications, follow-ups, suture removal). Services that can be billed separately during global periods include: unrelated E/M services (with modifier 24), treatment of complications requiring return to operating room (modifier 78), and staged procedures (modifier 58). The global period starts the day of surgery. Billing separately for services included in the global period is considered unbundling fraud unless appropriate modifiers are used. Medicare and most payers follow global surgery rules, though some commercial payers have different policies.', 'A surgeon performs a knee arthroscopy (90-day global period) on February 1st. Post-operative visits on February 10th, February 28th, and March 15th are included in the original surgery payment and cannot be separately billed. However, on March 1st, the patient returns with an unrelated shoulder problem. The shoulder visit can be billed with modifier 24 (99213-24) to indicate an unrelated E/M service during the global period.', 'Global period rules prevent duplicate billing for services included in surgical payment. Violating global period rules (billing for included services without appropriate modifiers) triggers audits and recoupment demands. Conversely, providers must understand they cannot bill for routine post-op care during globals - attempting to do so wastes billing effort and creates denials. Using correct modifiers enables billing for truly separate services during globals, capturing legitimate revenue.', 'Medical Coding', ARRAY['Surgical Package', 'Modifier 24', 'Modifier 58', 'Bundling']),

('Incident-to Billing', 'Medicare billing provision allowing services provided by non-physician practitioners to be billed under a supervising physician''s NPI at higher rates.', 'Incident-to billing allows services provided by nurse practitioners, physician assistants, and other qualified non-physician practitioners (NPPs) to be billed under the supervising physician''s name at 100% of the physician fee schedule rate, rather than the 85% rate for NPP services. Requirements include: service must be integral to physician''s service, physician must be present in the office suite (not necessarily in the room), service must be established patient (not new), physician must have personally performed initial service, and physician must remain actively involved in ongoing care. Incident-to is optional - NPPs can always bill under their own NPI. Violating incident-to rules can result in overpayment recoupment. Documentation must show physician involvement.', 'Dr. Smith (physician) sees a patient for diabetes management, establishes a treatment plan, and documents the initial visit. Two weeks later, Sarah Jones, NP, sees the same patient for diabetes follow-up per Dr. Smith''s plan. Dr. Smith is present in the office suite. This visit can be billed incident-to under Dr. Smith''s NPI at 100% of the fee schedule ($110). If billed under the NP''s NPI directly, Medicare would pay 85% ($93.50). However, if the NP sees a new patient, incident-to cannot be used regardless of physician presence.', 'Incident-to billing increases revenue by 15-18% for NPP services compared to direct NPP billing. However, incorrect incident-to billing is a major audit target. Many practices struggle with proper incident-to rules, leading to overpayments and recoupment. Some practices choose to always bill NPP services under the NPP''s NPI to avoid compliance risk, accepting the 85% payment. Understanding when incident-to applies and when it doesn''t is essential for practices employing NPPs.', 'Billing Process', ARRAY['Non-Physician Practitioner', 'Medicare', 'NPI', 'Supervising Physician']),

('Credentialing', 'The process of verifying healthcare provider qualifications and obtaining approval to participate in insurance networks.', 'Credentialing involves submitting detailed information about providers'' education, training, licensure, certifications, work history, and malpractice coverage to insurance companies and hospitals. The process typically takes 90-180 days and includes: primary source verification (contacting schools, boards, etc.), background checks, malpractice claims history review, and committee review. Providers must be credentialed before billing insurance companies as in-network providers. Re-credentialing is required every 2-3 years. CAQH ProView is a centralized database many payers use for credentialing information. Incomplete or delayed credentialing prevents providers from being paid as in-network, forcing out-of-network rates or cash-only practice. Hospital credentialing is separate and required for admitting privileges.', 'A new physician joins a practice. The practice administrator submits credentialing applications to 15 insurance companies with: medical school diploma, board certification, medical license, DEA certificate, malpractice insurance, work history, and references. After 4 months, the physician is credentialed with 12 payers and can begin billing as an in-network provider. The 3 slower payers take 6 months, during which the physician''s services must be billed at out-of-network rates or credited back to patients.', 'Incomplete or delayed credentialing directly impacts practice revenue. New providers cannot generate in-network revenue until credentialing is complete. Starting credentialing applications 6+ months before a provider''s start date prevents revenue loss. Re-credentialing must be tracked and completed before expiration to prevent loss of in-network status. Many practices outsource credentialing to specialized firms due to its complexity and administrative burden. Credentialing errors or omissions can delay the process significantly.', 'Practice Management', ARRAY['CAQH', 'Payer Contracting', 'In-Network Provider', 'Provider Enrollment']),

('Out-of-Network (OON)', 'Healthcare providers who do not have contracts with a patient''s insurance company.', 'Out-of-network providers have not contracted with a payer and are not bound by fee schedules or billing rules applicable to in-network providers. Implications include: higher patient cost-sharing (higher deductibles, coinsurance, copays), balance billing is allowed (billing patients for the difference between charges and insurance payment), lower insurance payment (often based on UCR rather than contracted rates), and prior authorization may not apply. Some plans have no OON benefits, paying zero for OON services. OON billing can create significant patient balance billing issues and collection challenges. Some high-demand providers choose to be OON from all or most insurances, operating on a cash or limited insurance model. Surprise billing legislation has limited balance billing in certain emergency and facility situations.', 'A patient with Blue Cross insurance visits an out-of-network specialist. The specialist charges $500 for the visit. Blue Cross has no contracted rate, so they pay based on their UCR determination of $300. After the patient''s $2,000 OON deductible is met, Blue Cross pays 60% ($180), the patient owes 40% coinsurance ($120), plus the balance between charges and UCR ($200), for a total patient responsibility of $320. If the provider was in-network, the patient would owe only a $50 copay.', 'OON status significantly affects patient costs and practice collections. Patients increasingly avoid OON providers due to high costs. Practices should clearly communicate OON status upfront and collect payment at time of service when possible, as OON patient collection rates are much lower than in-network. For high-value specialists, OON can be financially viable, but most practices need in-network contracts to attract patients. The No Surprises Act limits balance billing for certain OON emergency and ancillary services at in-network facilities.', 'Insurance Terms', ARRAY['In-Network', 'Balance Billing', 'UCR', 'Surprise Billing']),

('Balance Billing', 'Billing patients for the difference between provider charges and insurance payments.', 'Balance billing occurs when providers bill patients for amounts beyond insurance payments and patient cost-sharing. For in-network providers, balance billing is generally prohibited by contracts - providers must accept the allowed amount and can only bill patients for deductible, coinsurance, copays, and non-covered services. For out-of-network providers, balance billing is typically allowed - they can bill patients for the full difference between charges and insurance payment. The No Surprises Act (effective 2022) prohibits surprise balance billing in certain situations: emergency services, ancillary services at in-network facilities, and air ambulance services. Balance billing is controversial and can create significant financial hardship for patients. Some states have additional balance billing protections beyond federal law.', 'Scenario 1: In-network provider charges $500, allowed amount is $300, insurance pays $240, patient coinsurance is $60. The provider must accept $300 total and CANNOT balance bill the patient for the $200 difference between charges and allowed amount. Scenario 2: Out-of-network provider charges $500, insurance considers UCR to be $300 and pays $180. The provider CAN balance bill the patient for the $200 difference, plus the patient''s coinsurance, creating a total patient bill of $320.', 'Balance billing protections are essential for patient financial protection. In-network providers violating balance billing prohibitions face contract violations and potential legal action. For out-of-network providers, balance billing creates collection challenges and patient dissatisfaction. The No Surprises Act creates complex new requirements for OON providers in specific situations, with severe penalties for violations. Practices must understand when balance billing is allowed versus prohibited.', 'Financial Terms', ARRAY['Out-of-Network', 'In-Network', 'Surprise Billing', 'Allowed Amount']),

('Surprise Billing', 'Unexpected medical bills received when patients unknowingly receive care from out-of-network providers.', 'Surprise billing typically occurs in two scenarios: emergency care at an OON facility, or facility-based services (anesthesiology, radiology, pathology, etc.) provided by OON providers at in-network facilities. The No Surprises Act (2022) protects patients from surprise billing by: prohibiting balance billing in protected situations, establishing independent dispute resolution (IDR) processes for payment disputes, requiring good faith estimates for uninsured/self-pay patients, and allowing patients to consent to OON care when time permits. Protected services include: emergency services, ancillary services at in-network facilities, and air ambulance. Providers violating surprise billing protections face civil monetary penalties up to $10,000 per violation. The IDR process resolves payment disputes between providers and payers.', 'A patient with Blue Cross has emergency appendicitis and is taken to an in-network hospital. The emergency physician and anesthesiologist are out-of-network with Blue Cross. Previously, the patient would receive surprise bills from these OON providers. Under the No Surprises Act, the patient is protected - they pay only their in-network cost-sharing, and the OON providers cannot balance bill. If the providers and Blue Cross dispute payment, they use the IDR process to resolve the amount owed.', 'Surprise billing protections dramatically changed OON billing practices and revenue for certain specialties. Providers must understand when they cannot balance bill despite being OON. The IDR process is complex and expensive ($50-$350 filing fees), making small disputes uneconomical. Good faith estimate requirements create new administrative burdens. Violations result in significant penalties. Many facility-based providers are joining networks or negotiating with hospitals to avoid surprise billing issues.', 'Compliance & Regulations', ARRAY['Balance Billing', 'Out-of-Network', 'No Surprises Act', 'Independent Dispute Resolution']),

('Usual, Customary, and Reasonable (UCR)', 'A method used by insurance companies to determine payment amounts for out-of-network services.', 'UCR methodology establishes payment for OON services based on what providers in the same geographic area typically charge for similar services. UCR rates are typically less than provider charges but more than in-network contracted rates. Payers use various data sources for UCR: proprietary databases, FAIR Health database, Medicare fee schedules plus a percentage, or percentile rankings of area charges (e.g., 80th percentile of charges in the region). UCR determinations are often opaque and can be disputed by providers. Some payers define UCR very narrowly to minimize OON payments. The difference between provider charges and UCR payments can be balanced billed to patients (if allowed). Understanding how payers calculate UCR helps OON providers set appropriate fee schedules.', 'An OON surgeon charges $10,000 for a procedure. The patient''s insurance calculates UCR as $6,000 (based on 80th percentile of charges in the area). After the patient''s deductible and coinsurance, insurance pays $4,500. The surgeon can balance bill the patient for the $4,000 difference between charges ($10,000) and UCR ($6,000), plus the patient owes the coinsurance on the UCR amount. Total patient responsibility: $5,500.', 'UCR methodology significantly impacts OON reimbursement and patient balance billing. Providers have limited ability to influence payer UCR determinations, but can negotiate in some cases. Understanding typical UCR rates in your area helps set realistic fee schedules. Large gaps between charges and UCR create patient affordability issues and collection challenges. Some states regulate UCR methodologies to ensure fairness. The No Surprises Act established qualifying payment amounts (QPA) as a UCR replacement for surprise billing situations.', 'Financial Terms', ARRAY['Out-of-Network', 'Balance Billing', 'Allowed Amount', 'Fee Schedule']),

('EOB Code', 'Standardized codes on Explanation of Benefits/remittance advice explaining claim actions.', 'EOB codes include: CARC (Claim Adjustment Reason Codes) explaining why adjustments were made, RARC (Remittance Advice Remark Codes) providing additional information, and claim status codes. Common CARC codes: CO (Contractual Obligation), PR (Patient Responsibility), OA (Other Adjustment). Common specific codes: CO-45 (charges exceed fee schedule), PR-1 (deductible), PR-2 (coinsurance), CO-16 (missing information), CO-50 (non-covered services), CO-197 (precertification absent). Understanding EOB codes is essential for determining appropriate follow-up: some codes indicate denials requiring correction and resubmission, others indicate final adjustments, and some indicate patient responsibility. Billers must learn common codes for their payers and specialties.', 'A remittance advice shows: Line 1 - Code CO-45 with $150 adjustment (charge exceeds contracted amount - contractual adjustment, expected). Line 2 - Code CO-16 with $0 payment (missing information - needs correction). Line 3 - Code PR-1 with $200 patient responsibility (patient deductible - bill patient). The biller knows: Line 1 is routine, Line 2 requires claim correction and resubmission, Line 3 requires patient statement generation.', 'EOB codes are the "language" of claim adjudication. Without understanding codes, billing staff cannot determine appropriate actions for each claim. Misinterpreting codes leads to incorrect follow-up: billing patients for amounts not their responsibility, missing opportunities to correct denials, or attempting to rework final adjustments. Training staff on common EOB codes specific to their specialty and payers improves denial recovery and reduces wasted effort on uncorrectable denials.', 'Claims & Denials', ARRAY['CARC Code', 'RARC Code', 'EOB', 'Remittance Advice']),

('Clean Claim Rate', 'The percentage of claims that pass all edits and are accepted for payment without needing corrections.', 'Clean claim rate measures first-pass claim success and is calculated as: (Claims accepted without rejection or denial ÷ Total claims submitted) × 100. Industry best practices target 95%+ clean claim rates. Clean claims are accepted and paid quickly, while rejected claims require rework, delaying payment and increasing costs. Common reasons for "unclean" claims: demographic errors, insurance information errors, coding mistakes, missing authorizations, and documentation issues. Technology tools improving clean claim rates include: real-time eligibility verification, claim scrubbing software, EHR-PM integration for accurate charge capture, and automated coding tools. Clean claim rate is a primary KPI for revenue cycle performance.', 'Practice A submits 1,000 claims per month with a 92% clean claim rate - 920 are accepted immediately, 80 are rejected or denied. Practice B submits 1,000 claims with a 97% clean claim rate - 970 accepted, 30 rejected or denied. Practice B has 50 fewer claims requiring rework, saving $1,250+ in administrative costs monthly ($25 per rework), and receives payment 15-20 days faster for those 50 claims, significantly improving cash flow.', 'Clean claim rate directly impacts days in A/R, cash flow, and administrative costs. Improving clean claim rate by just 2-3% can save thousands in rework costs and accelerate cash flow significantly. Claims rejected on first submission are paid 30-60+ days later than clean claims, affecting working capital. Root cause analysis of rejection/denial reasons identifies opportunities for process improvements, staff training, or technology upgrades that improve clean claim rates.', 'Revenue Cycle', ARRAY['Claim Rejection', 'First Pass Resolution Rate', 'Days in A/R', 'Claim Scrubbing']),

('Charge Entry', 'The process of recording billable services into the practice management system for claim generation.', 'Charge entry is a critical step in the revenue cycle where services are translated into billable codes and entered into billing systems. Methods include: paper encounter forms/superbills sent to billing staff, direct EHR charge capture by providers, and automated rules-based charge capture from documentation. Charge entry includes: patient demographics, service dates, procedure codes (CPT/HCPCS), diagnosis codes (ICD-10), modifiers, units, and charges. Charge entry must occur promptly (ideally within 24 hours) to meet timely filing requirements and maximize cash flow. Charge entry errors cause claim denials - incorrect codes, missing modifiers, wrong diagnosis codes, or data entry mistakes. Quality controls include: charge entry audits, matching to schedules, and automated validation against documentation.', 'A surgeon performs three procedures. The EHR prompts for charge capture: (1) Primary procedure with CPT code, diagnosis codes, and modifiers, (2) Second procedure with modifier 51, (3) Third procedure with modifier 51 and appropriate bundling checks. The charges are electronically captured in the PM system, creating a claim ready for submission. Previously, the surgeon would have completed a paper superbill that billing staff manually entered, creating a 2-3 day delay and potential transcription errors.', 'Charge entry quality directly affects revenue. Missed charges create revenue leakage - studies show 1-3% of charges are missed without proper capture systems. Delayed charge entry increases days in A/R and risks timely filing. Charge entry errors create denials requiring rework. Automated charge capture from EHRs reduces errors and delays compared to paper-based systems. However, automation requires proper clinical documentation - inadequate notes result in missed or incorrect charge capture.', 'Billing Process', ARRAY['Charge Capture', 'Encounter Form', 'Revenue Leakage', 'Superbill']),

('Payment Posting', 'The process of recording insurance and patient payments in the practice management system.', 'Payment posting includes: matching payments to specific claims, recording payment amounts, applying adjustments, identifying denial reasons, calculating patient responsibility, and reconciling payments to bank deposits. Payment posting can be manual (from paper EOBs) or electronic (auto-posting from ERA files). Accurate payment posting is essential for: maintaining correct A/R balances, identifying underpayments, generating accurate patient statements, and financial reporting. Payment posting must identify: paid claims (move to zero balance), partially paid claims (analyze for underpayment or patient responsibility), and denied claims (route to denial management). Daily payment posting prevents backlogs and keeps A/R current. Payment posting accuracy affects all downstream processes.', 'A practice receives an ERA from Aetna with $45,000 in payments for 150 claims. The billing staff (or automated system) posts each payment: applying the payment to the correct claim, taking contractual adjustments, posting denial codes for 8 denied claims (routing to denial queue), calculating patient balances for 25 claims with deductible/coinsurance (generating statements), and verifying the total matches the bank deposit of $45,000.', 'Accurate payment posting is essential for financial accuracy and A/R integrity. Posting errors create false A/R balances, missed denials, and incorrect patient billing. Delayed payment posting increases days in A/R and hides revenue cycle issues. Automated ERA posting dramatically improves efficiency but requires exception monitoring - not all payments auto-post correctly. Payment posting reveals underpayments, denials, and trends requiring follow-up. Without proper posting, practices cannot identify revenue recovery opportunities.', 'Billing Process', ARRAY['ERA', 'EOB', 'Remittance Advice', 'Reconciliation']),

('Revenue Leakage', 'Lost revenue due to inefficiencies or errors in the revenue cycle process.', 'Revenue leakage occurs throughout the revenue cycle from multiple sources: missed charges (services provided but not billed), coding errors (undercoding or unbundling failures), denied claims not worked, timely filing denials, charge capture failures, authorization lapses, contract underpayments not identified, and patient balance write-offs. Studies estimate practices lose 1-5% of potential revenue to leakage. Causes include: manual processes prone to error, lack of charge reconciliation, inadequate denial management, poor payer contract compliance tracking, and insufficient revenue cycle analytics. Preventing leakage requires: automated charge capture, charge reconciliation against schedules, denial management processes, contract compliance monitoring, and regular revenue cycle audits.', 'A busy surgical practice analyzes its revenue leakage and finds: $15,000 monthly in missed charges for supplies and ancillary services not captured, $8,000 in denied claims not worked, $12,000 in coding underpayments (could bill higher levels with better documentation), and $5,000 in contract underpayments not identified and appealed. Total leakage: $40,000 per month or $480,000 annually. Implementing charge capture improvements, denial management workflows, and contract monitoring recovers 75% ($360,000 annually).', 'Revenue leakage directly reduces practice profitability with no corresponding cost reduction - it''s revenue that should have been captured but was lost. Even 1-2% leakage equals hundreds of thousands for busy practices. Revenue leakage is often invisible without specific analysis. RCM technology, process improvements, and analytics can identify and minimize leakage. The ROI on leakage reduction initiatives is typically excellent - recovered revenue flows directly to the bottom line.', 'Revenue Cycle', ARRAY['Charge Capture', 'Denial Management', 'Undercoding', 'Contract Compliance']),

('Payer Contract', 'Legal agreements between healthcare providers and insurance companies defining reimbursement terms and requirements.', 'Payer contracts establish: fee schedules/allowed amounts for services, payment timelines (typically 30-45 days), claims submission requirements, authorization requirements, patient billing restrictions, quality metrics, provider responsibilities, termination clauses, and dispute resolution processes. Contracts vary significantly between payers - some pay percentage of Medicare, others use proprietary fee schedules, some include pay-for-performance bonuses. Contracts should be reviewed carefully before signing and periodically (every 2-3 years) for renegotiation opportunities. Understanding contract terms is essential for: compliance, revenue maximization, identifying underpayments, and strategic payer decisions. Many practices don''t retain or review their contracts, missing underpayments and compliance requirements.', 'A primary care practice reviews its Blue Cross contract and finds: (1) Primary care visits are paid at 140% of Medicare, (2) Claims must be paid within 30 days of clean claim submission, (3) The practice cannot balance bill patients beyond cost-sharing, (4) Prior authorization is required for advanced imaging, (5) The practice can terminate with 90 days'' written notice. When Blue Cross doesn''t pay within 30 days, the practice references the contract to demand timely payment, recovering interest on late payments per the contract.', 'Payer contracts directly determine practice revenue - fee schedule terms can vary 20-50% between payers. Practices often accept unfavorable contracts without negotiation, leaving significant revenue on the table. Understanding contract terms enables identification of payer underpayments or contract violations. Contract language around termination, patient billing, and quality metrics has major operational and financial implications. Legal review of contracts prevents agreeing to unfavorable or ambiguous terms.', 'Practice Management', ARRAY['Fee Schedule', 'Allowed Amount', 'Credentialing', 'Contract Negotiation']);

-- Add more terms covering remaining categories
INSERT INTO glossary_terms (term, definition, detailed_explanation, example, why_it_matters, category, related_terms) VALUES
('MIPS', 'Merit-based Incentive Payment System - Medicare quality reporting and payment adjustment program.', 'MIPS is part of the Quality Payment Program under MACRA, affecting Medicare Part B providers. MIPS combines four performance categories into a composite score: Quality (clinical outcome measures, 40%), Promoting Interoperability (meaningful use of EHR, 25%), Improvement Activities (care improvement and care coordination, 15%), and Cost (cost efficiency measures, 20%). Final scores (0-100) determine payment adjustments up to ±9% on all Medicare Part B payments. Reporting thresholds change annually. Eligible clinicians include physicians, PAs, NPs, CRNAs, and others meeting volume thresholds. Alternatives to MIPS include: APMs (Alternative Payment Models) and ACOs (Accountable Care Organizations). MIPS requires annual data submission through registries, EHRs, or claims.', 'A family medicine physician participates in MIPS for 2024: Reports 6 quality measures (scores 80/100), achieves promoting interoperability requirements (100%), completes improvement activities (full credit), and has average cost performance. Final MIPS score: 85. This scores above the national mean, resulting in a +2.5% payment adjustment on all 2026 Medicare Part B payments. If the practice bills $500,000 to Medicare Part B annually, this equals $12,500 in bonus payments.', 'MIPS creates significant financial risk - penalty adjustments reduce revenue while positive adjustments increase it. Failing to participate results in automatic penalties (-9% in 2024). MIPS reporting is complex, requiring dedicated resources, technology, and expertise. Many practices struggle with MIPS compliance, losing bonus opportunities or incurring penalties. MIPS affects all Medicare Part B payments, making even small percentage adjustments financially significant for Medicare-heavy practices.', 'Compliance & Regulations', ARRAY['Quality Payment Program', 'MACRA', 'Meaningful Use', 'Value-Based Care']),

('ACO', 'Accountable Care Organization - groups of providers who coordinate care to improve quality and reduce costs, sharing in savings achieved.', 'ACOs are Medicare programs where provider groups take responsibility for quality and total cost of care for assigned Medicare beneficiaries. Key features: shared savings model (ACOs that reduce costs while meeting quality benchmarks share in savings), quality measures (patient experience, care coordination, preventive health), and downside risk models (some ACOs risk penalties if costs exceed targets). Types include: Medicare Shared Savings Program (MSSP), Next Gen ACO, and others. ACOs require care coordination infrastructure, data analytics, population health management, and risk stratification capabilities. ACOs represent a shift from fee-for-service to value-based payment. Successful ACOs can earn significant shared savings payments.', 'A primary care group forms an MSSP ACO with 10,000 assigned Medicare beneficiaries. The ACO implements: care coordination programs, high-risk patient outreach, chronic disease management, and reduced preventable hospitalizations. In year one, the ACO reduces total cost of care by $2 million while achieving quality benchmarks. Under shared savings rules, the ACO earns $1 million in shared savings payments (50% of savings), distributed among participating providers.', 'ACOs represent a major shift in payment methodology from volume to value. Successful ACO participation can generate significant additional revenue beyond traditional fee-for-service. However, ACOs require infrastructure investment, care transformation, and financial risk. ACO participation affects practice operations, workflows, and clinical protocols. ACO quality measures influence care delivery. As Medicare and commercial payers expand value-based models, ACO experience becomes increasingly important.', 'Reimbursement', ARRAY['Value-Based Care', 'Shared Savings', 'MIPS', 'Population Health']),

('Explanation of Medical Benefits (EOMB)', 'Document explaining what Medicare covers and doesn''t cover for specific services, similar to an EOB.', 'EOMB is Medicare''s term for the explanation of benefits sent to beneficiaries after Medicare processes claims. The EOMB shows: services received, service dates, amounts charged by providers, Medicare-approved amounts, Medicare payment, patient responsibility, and reasons for any denials or reductions. Providers also receive a Medicare Remittance Notice (MRN) with similar information. EOMBs help beneficiaries understand their Medicare benefits, verify services received, identify billing errors, and track their deductible and out-of-pocket spending. Medicare requires beneficiaries to receive EOMBs quarterly or after each claim processed, depending on beneficiary preferences. Medicare now offers electronic EOMBs through online accounts.', 'A Medicare beneficiary receives an EOMB showing: Doctor visit on 3/15/24, Amount charged: $200, Medicare approved amount: $120, Medicare paid (80%): $96, Your responsibility (20%): $24. The EOMB explains: "This is your 20% coinsurance after you met your deductible." The beneficiary verifies the visit occurred, the amount is correct, and pays the $24 balance.', 'EOMBs provide transparency into Medicare billing and payments. Beneficiaries should review EOMBs to identify billing errors, incorrect services, or potential fraud. For providers, explaining EOMBs to patients reduces billing inquiries and payment delays. Many beneficiaries don''t understand EOMBs, viewing them as bills (they''re not), requiring patient education. Clear EOMB explanation at time of service prevents confusion and improves collections.', 'Insurance Terms', ARRAY['EOB', 'Medicare', 'Patient Statement', 'Medicare Summary Notice']),

('Meaningful Use', 'Now called Promoting Interoperability - incentive program for adoption and meaningful use of certified EHR technology.', 'Meaningful Use (now Promoting Interoperability under MIPS) incentivized EHR adoption through payments and penalties. Three stages progressed from basic EHR adoption to advanced health information exchange and patient engagement. Requirements included: e-prescribing, clinical decision support, electronic health information exchange, patient access to health information, and clinical quality measure reporting. Providers meeting requirements received incentive payments and avoided Medicare penalties. As of 2023, Meaningful Use is incorporated into MIPS Promoting Interoperability category. Eligible professionals, eligible hospitals, and critical access hospitals participated. The program succeeded in increasing EHR adoption from 10% (2008) to over 85% (2021).', 'A physician practice using a certified EHR meets Promoting Interoperability requirements for 2024: (1) E-prescribing for 80%+ of prescriptions, (2) Health Information Exchange with external providers, (3) Providing patients electronic access to records, (4) Conducting security risk assessments. Meeting these requirements earns the full 25 points for Promoting Interoperability in their MIPS score, contributing to positive payment adjustments.', 'Meaningful Use drove widespread EHR adoption, transforming healthcare delivery. However, compliance burdens and EHR usability issues created provider frustration. The shift to Promoting Interoperability reduced regulatory burden while maintaining focus on interoperability and patient engagement. Practices must maintain Promoting Interoperability compliance to maximize MIPS scores and avoid penalties. EHR vendors must maintain certification to support practices.', 'Healthcare IT', ARRAY['MIPS', 'EHR', 'Interoperability', 'Quality Payment Program']),

('Unbundling', 'The practice of billing separately for services that should be billed together as a single code, considered fraudulent if done intentionally.', 'Unbundling violations occur when providers bill multiple codes for component services instead of using a single comprehensive code. Common examples: billing both tonsillectomy and adenoidectomy codes separately when a combination code exists, billing excision of lesion and closure separately when closure is included, or billing global surgical package components separately. Unbundling increases reimbursement improperly. NCCI (National Correct Coding Initiative) edits prevent most unbundling, bundling component codes automatically. Intentional unbundling is fraud, resulting in: payment recoupment, civil monetary penalties, program exclusion, and potential criminal prosecution. Unintentional unbundling creates denials and audit risks. Proper coding training and claim scrubbing prevent unbundling errors.', 'Example of unbundling: A surgeon removes skin lesions and bills: 11400 (excision), 12001 (simple repair), 99213 (E/M same day). However, simple repair is bundled into excision per NCCI - only 11400 and 99213-25 (if separately identifiable) should be billed. The payer bundles 12001 into 11400, denying separate payment. If the provider continues billing this way knowingly to gain extra payment, it becomes fraud.', 'Unbundling is a serious compliance violation that providers must understand and avoid. Unintentional unbundling creates denials and rework but isn''t fraudulent. Intentional unbundling constitutes fraud with severe penalties. Practices must: train coders on bundling rules, use NCCI edit-checking tools, and audit coding patterns for potential unbundling. When services are truly separate and distinct, appropriate modifiers (59, XE, XP, XS, XU) can override bundling edits and allow separate payment.', 'Compliance & Regulations', ARRAY['Bundling', 'NCCI Edits', 'Modifier 59', 'Fraud and Abuse']),

('NCCI Edits', 'National Correct Coding Initiative - Medicare coding edits preventing improper code combinations and unbundling.', 'NCCI edits identify code pairs that should not be billed together because: one service is bundled into another, services are mutually exclusive, or procedures don''t make anatomical sense together. Two types: Column 1/Column 2 edits (Column 2 code is bundled into Column 1), and Mutually Exclusive Edits (procedures that cannot reasonably be done together). NCCI assigns modifier indicators: 0 (bundling cannot be overridden), 1 (appropriate modifier can override bundling), or 9 (not applicable). CMS updates NCCI edits quarterly. While designed for Medicare, most commercial payers also use NCCI edits. Understanding NCCI helps: avoid denials, use modifiers appropriately, and identify billing errors. NCCI edit-checking software flags violations before claim submission.', 'A provider bills CPT codes 99213 (office visit) and 11200 (skin lesion removal) on the same day. Without a modifier, NCCI would bundle the E/M into the procedure. However, if the E/M service was separately identifiable (e.g., the visit addressed diabetes management unrelated to the lesion), modifier 25 can be appended to 99213, overriding the NCCI edit and allowing payment for both services: 99213-25 and 11200.', 'NCCI edits prevent improper payments and guide correct coding practices. Understanding NCCI helps practices avoid denials and use modifiers appropriately. Many denials result from NCCI violations that could be prevented with proper coding or modifier use. NCCI edit files are publicly available and should be referenced when coding complex scenarios. Claim scrubbing software with NCCI edit-checking catches most violations before submission. When NCCI edits bundle separately identifiable services, appropriate modifier use enables payment.', 'Medical Coding', ARRAY['Bundling', 'Unbundling', 'Modifier 59', 'CPT Code']),

('Self-Pay', 'Patients who pay for healthcare services directly without using insurance.', 'Self-pay patients include: uninsured individuals, patients with insurance who choose not to use it (sometimes services are cheaper cash-pay than through high-deductible insurance), patients receiving non-covered services, and international patients. Self-pay requires: verifying patient will pay out-of-pocket, providing cost estimates upfront, collecting payment at time of service (preferred) or establishing payment plans, offering prompt-pay discounts, and ensuring no prohibited dual-billing (if patient has insurance, can''t balance bill and bill insurance). Self-pay rates are often discounted from full charges but higher than insurance contracted rates. Self-pay collection rates are much lower than insurance collections, requiring point-of-service collection and payment plans. Many practices struggle with self-pay patients due to unpredictable payment.', 'A patient without insurance schedules a procedure costing $5,000 at standard rates. The practice offers a self-pay rate of $3,000 (60% of charges), a 10% discount for payment-in-full at service ($2,700), or a 6-month payment plan ($500/month). The patient chooses the payment plan, pays $500 deposit at time of service, and signs an agreement for monthly payments. This approach collects more reliably than sending bills after service.', 'Self-pay patients create collection challenges - post-service collection rates are 50-70% at best. Pre-service estimates, payment plans, and point-of-service collection dramatically improve self-pay collections. Some practices require payment before service for elective procedures. Self-pay discounts must comply with payer contracts and fraud/abuse laws - different rates for insured versus uninsured patients are generally acceptable, but waiving cost-sharing for insured patients can violate Anti-Kickback Statute. Self-pay revenue is growing with high-deductible plans.', 'Financial Terms', ARRAY['Patient Responsibility', 'Payment Plan', 'Prompt-Pay Discount', 'Patient Collections']),

('Bad Debt', 'Patient account balances that have been deemed uncollectible and written off.', 'Bad debt occurs when patient balances cannot be collected despite collection efforts. Typical progression: statement generation → phone calls → collection letters → payment plans offered → final notice → write-off as bad debt or transfer to external collections. Most practices write off balances after 90-180 days of unsuccessful collection efforts. Bad debt percentages vary by specialty, patient demographics, and collection processes, typically ranging from 2-10% of patient responsibility amounts. High bad debt indicates: inadequate point-of-service collections, ineffective collection processes, inaccurate patient estimates, or demographic challenges. Reducing bad debt requires: upfront payment collection, payment plans, financial counseling, and clear financial policies. Bad debt write-offs may be tax-deductible under specific IRS rules.', 'A patient owes $1,200 after insurance pays their portion. The practice: sends 3 statements over 90 days, calls twice (no answer), sends certified letter, offers payment plan (patient doesn''t respond). After 120 days and reasonable collection efforts, the practice writes off the balance as bad debt. If referred to external collections, the agency might recover 20-40% ($240-$480), with half going to the agency and half to the practice.', 'Bad debt directly reduces revenue - it''s money legally owed but uncollectable. Every 1% reduction in bad debt improves profitability significantly. Point-of-service collection is the most effective bad debt prevention - collection rates drop from 90%+ at time of service to 50-70% after 30 days. Payment plans, accurate patient estimates, and proactive financial counseling reduce bad debt. Many practices accept high bad debt as inevitable, but best practices can reduce bad debt rates by 30-50%.', 'Financial Terms', ARRAY['Write-off', 'Patient Collections', 'Collection Rate', 'Payment Plan']);

